RStudio Exercise 2

The dataset is a student survey collected by Kimmo Vehkalahti. In the data wrangling exercise, I chose the variables relevant for this assignment: here we have 7 variables and 166 observations. The structure of the dataset is seen below. There are more women than men among the respondents, the median age is 22. Variable Attitude measures the students attitudes towards statistics. Variables deep, stra, and surf measure the different approaches to learning: The variable deep consists of 12 different items measuring the deep approach towards learning, which refers the intention to maximize understanding and a true commitment to learning. The variable stra refers to Strategic approach and it consists of 8 different items. It measures the way students organize their studing. Lastly, variable surf refers to Surface approach and consists of 12 different items measuring memorizing without understanding, with a serious lack of personal engagement in the learning proces. The variable Points measures the students success at the exam. Students who received 0 points were omitted from the study.

Here we see the linear model where the success at the exam is the dependent variable (Points), and the attitude towards statistics (Attitude), the strategic studying (stra), and the surface studying (surf) are indenpendent variables. Attitude has positive and statistically significant correlation with the points from the exam: the better the attitude, the better the success at the exam. When attitude increases by one unit, the average change in points is 0.34 units, given that the other variables (here stra and surf) do not change. In this model, stratetic and surface studying are not statistically significantly associated with the dependent variable, at least when the. The model explains roughly twenty percent of the variance of this phenomenon.

In my final model there is only one explanatory factor: the attitude. When the attitude towards statistics increases by one unit, the average change in the points is 0.35 units. Multiple R-squared tells how much of the variance in the dependent variable can be explained by the independent variables. This model explains 19 % of the variation in the dependent variable (the points from the exam). Every time we add an independent variable to the model, the R-squared value will increase. Yet, we do not know if the increase in R-squared value is caused by the actual predictive power of the new variable, or just by chance alone.Adjusted R-squared provides the same information as R-squared but adjusts for the number of terms in the model. It decreases when the new variable does not have any real impact on the predicted value. (In this assingment, they are almost the same because we do not have many variables.)

Linear model have several assumptions, and how well the model describes the phenomenon we are studying, depends on how well these assumptions fit the reality. It is assumed that (1) the relationship between the independent and dependent variable is linear, (2) that the errors are normally distributed, (3) not correlated, and (4) have a constant variance. Prediction errors are called residuals and the model is found by minimizing the sum of residuals. Hence, analyzing the residuals of the model is a good method for analyzing the validity of the assumptions.

QQ-plot is a method for studying the normality assumption. The better the points fit into the line, the better the fit with the normality assumption. In this picture we see that the majority of the observations fit to the normality assumption, only a few extreme values have weaker fit. Yet, the perfect fit can only be found with the synthetic data and I think our dataset passes this test.

plot(lin_reg3, which=c(2))

The constant variance assumption implies that the size of the errors should not depend on the explanatory variables. This is explored with a scatter plot of residuals versus model predictions. In the picture, residuals seem to be quite evenly distributed, we do not see any patterns in the picture but the spread of the dots seems reasonable random.

plot(lin_reg3, which=c(1))

Leverage measures the impact of a single observation to the model.Residuals vs leverage plot can help identify which observations have an usually high impact. There does not seem to be a problem with the leverage: no single outliers are having too much leverage to the model.

plot(lin_reg3, which=c(5))

Based on these diagnostic pictures, the linear model seems to fit the dataset.

This dataset is retrieved from the UCI Machine Learning Repository which is a source for open data. The data contain two identical questionnaires related to secondary school student alcohol comsumption in Portugal. For this exercise, two surveys were combined to one dataset. This final dataset contains 382 observations and 35 variables describing the participants and their families. More information about the data can be found here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/STUDENT+ALCOHOL+CONSUMPTION.

My hypothesis is that sex, the quality of family relationships, the amount of staying out with friends, and a will to go to higher education are associated to alcohol consumption in the following ways:

Hypothesis 1: Boys tend drink more alcohol than girls. Hypothesis 2: Students who have bad relationship with their family, tend to drink more alcohol. Hypothesis 3: Student who go out with friends a lot, tend to drink more alcohol. Hypothesis 4: Students who want to continue to higher education, tend to drink less alcohol.

Above we see the results of a logistic regression where the high use of alcohol is a dependent variable and sex, the quality of family relationship, the amount of going out with friends and will to continue to higher education are independent variables.As stated above, sex is associated with the high use of alcohol: boys tend to drink more alcohol. (Sex is a categorial variable and R orders the levels of the categorial variable alphabetically and takes the first as reference class. Hence, girls are here the reference class.) The quality of family relationship has an inverse association to the high use of alcohol. Going out with friends is positively associated with the high use of alcohol. Instead, the will to continue to higher education is not statistically significantly associated with the high use of alcohol. (Here the reference class is those who do not want to continue to higher education.)

#odds ratios and the confidence intervalls (95 %)
OR <- coef(logreg) %>% exp
CI <- confint(logreg) %>% exp

Above we see the odds ratios and confidence intervals (95 %). Boys have a higher odds of the high use of alcohol than girs (OR=2.5, CI=1.5-4.2). Yet, confidence intervalls are quite wide. However, this finding clearly supports the first hypothesis. The quality of the family relationship is inversely associated with a high use of alcohol (OR=0.6, CI=0.5-0.8): the better the relationship, the smaller the odds of a high use of alcohol. The association is not very strong, though, since the coefficient is quite small. However, this finding supports the second hypothesis. Going out with friends is associated with the high use of alcohol (OR=2.2, CI=1.8-2.9). Hence, also the third hypothesis is clearly supported by the model. A will to continue to higher education seems to be associated with the high use of alcohol in a hypothesized way: the odds for those who want to go to higher education is less than 1 (OR=0.6, CI=0.2-1.9). However, the confidence interval is huge so I conclude that the fourth hypothesis does not get support from the data. It seems that of the variables I studies, going out with friends is the best predictor of the high use of alcohol. It sounds logical: for many young people, drinking alcohol is related to social situations, such as going out with peers.

I test the predictive power of my model by calculating the proportion of correctly classified observations. The proportion of inccorrectly classified observations is the error of my model. I include only the variables wchich had a statistical relationship with high alcohol consumption according to my logistic regression model, hence I exclude the variable describing the will to continue to higher education.

#fit the model again, without the variable "higher"
logreg2 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + famrel + goout, data = uci, family = "binomial")
#predict the probability of high use of alcohol
probabilities <- predict(logreg2, type = "response")
#add the predicted probabilities to dataset
uci <- mutate(uci, probability = probabilities)
#use the probabilities to make a prediction of high use of alcohol
uci <- mutate(uci, prediction = probability >0.5 )

Next I define a loss function and compute the mean prediction error for my model.

#define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
#call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = uci$high_use, prob = uci$probability)
## [1] 0.2120419

We see that the training error of the model is 0.21. It means that, on average, 21 % of the predictions were wrong. Simple guessing method in a binary situation (e.g.flipping a symmetric coin) would have been right roughly in 50 % of the events. My model predicted accurately in 79 % of situations. Hence, my model performed better than just guessing.

As a bonus, I perform 10-fold cross-validation on my model. Cross-validation involves partitioning a sample of data into complementary subsets, performing the analysis on one subset (the training set), and validating the analysis on the other subset (the testing set). The process is repeated so that eventually all of the data is used for both the training and testing.

#install and use the package 
install.packages("boot", repos="http://cran.rstudio.com/")
library(boot)
#perform 10-fold cross-validation by using earlier created loss function
cv <- cv.glm(data = uci, cost = loss_func, glmfit = logreg2, K = 10)

Delta gives two values: The first component is the raw cross-validation estimate of prediction error. The second component is the adjusted cross-validation estimate. The adjustment is designed to compensate for the bias introduced by not using leave-one-out cross-validation.

#Print out the mean prediction error for the testing data.
cv$delta
## [1] 0.2172775 0.2138373

This week we use a Boston dataset which describes the Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston. More information about the dataset can be found here: https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html

Boston dataset has 506 observations and 14 variables. Variables describe, for instance, economic, demographic, and environmental factors of the area. Here are the descriptions of the variables:

  • crim=per capita crime rate by town
  • zn=proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • indus=proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • chas=Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • nox=nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • rm=average number of rooms per dwelling
  • age=proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
  • dis=weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres
  • rad=index of accessibility to radial highways
  • tax=full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
  • ptratio=pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • black=1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
  • lstat=lower status of the population (percent)
  • medv=median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

#the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric

Next I study how many clusters would be optimal for this dataset. I set the maximum clusters to 10. I look at how the total of within cluster sum of squares (WCSS) behaves when the number of cluster changes. The optimal number of clusters is when the total WCSS drops radically.

set.seed(123)
# determine the maximum number of clusters
k_max <- 10
# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})
# visualize the results
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type='b')

From the plot we see, that 2 clusters would be optimal for this data. I run the K-means clustering again, this time for two clusters. K-means might produce different results every time, because it randomly assigns the initial cluster centers. The function set.seed() can be used to deal with that.

#k-means clustering
set.seed(123)
km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers=2)
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

In the picture below we have the two clusters with different colours for each variable. For our main interest, crime rate, the two cluster structure is easy to see.

#the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows2 <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes2 <- as.numeric(km$cluster)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit2, dimen = 2, col=classes2, pch=classes)
lda.arrows2(lda.fit2, myscale = 2)

Describing the dataset

The human dataset originates from the United Nations Development Program. More information about the dataset can be found here: http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/human-development-index-hdi. In this assignment, I use the dataset which has 8 variables and 155 countries. The variables of the dataset describe health, economic and gender equality of each country. Below is the list of the variable names and descriptions.

  • GNI = Gross National Income per capita
  • Life.Exp = Life expectancy at birth
  • Edu.Exp = Expected years of schooling
  • Mat.Mor = Maternal mortality ratio
  • Ado.Birth = Adolescent birth rate
  • Parli.F = Percetange of female representatives in parliament
  • Edu2.FM = the ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education in each country
  • Labo.FM = the ratio of labour force participation of females and males in each country

Below is the summary of the data. We see that the variables have very different scales. The differences between the scales are important for later analyses.

GNI is also at least moderately associated with the ratio of female and male populations with secondary education (r=0.43), but - interestingly - GNI is not correlated with all of the variables describing gender equality. GNI is not associated with the ratio of labor force participation of females and males as well as with percentage of female representatives in parliament.

Principal Component Analysis

Non-standardized data

Next I perform principal component analysis (PCA) on the not standardized human data. My goal is to find the components that capture the most of the variance. PCA can be performed by two slightly different matrix decomposition methods from linear algebra: the Eigenvalue Decomposition and the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD). In this assignment, I used the SVD method. I use the prcomp() function which decompose a data matrix into a product of smaller matrices, which lets us extract the underlying principal components. This makes it possible to approximate a lower dimensional representation of the data by choosing only a few principal components.

pca_human <- prcomp(human)

In PCA, the data is first transformed to a new space with equal or less number of dimensions. These new features are called the principal components. The 1st principal component (PC1) captures the maximum amount of variance from the features in the original data. The 2nd principal component (PC2) is orthogonal to the first and it captures the maximum amount of variability left. The same is true for each principal component. They are all uncorrelated and each is less important than the previous one, in terms of captured variance. With our data, we found 8 principal components. Lets see the importance of different components.

summary(pca_human)

# draw a biplot
biplot(pca_human, cex = c(0.5, 0.8), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

This biplot suggests that almost all of the variance is caused by one GNI, Gross National Income per capita. PCA is sensitive to the relative scaling of the original features and assumes that features with larger variance are more important than features with smaller variance. GNI has the largest scale (min: 581, max: 123,100). Therefore Ill do the analysis again, but with this time by standardized data.

The results of the PCA with standardized data are clearly different. Now the first two components explain 53.6% and 16.2% of the variance in our dataset. The variables having strongest loadings on PC1 are maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate. The strongest negative loadings on PC1 are life expectancy, expected years of schooling, the ratio of females to males with secondary education, and gross national income per capita. The variables having strongest loadings on PC2 are the ratio of females to males in labor and female parliamentary representation. The first principal component seems to describe health and economic factors of the countries, and the second describes the gender equality in participating in politics and labor. Together these two component explained 70 percentages of the variance between countries.

From the biplot we see that, for instance, Iceland has high gender equality, giving birth is safe to a womans health, and women tend to participate in politics and labor force more than most of the countries. Many African and Asian countries such as Niger and Afghanistan, for instance, are poor countries where people have short life expectancy, women tend to have many children and giving birth is dangerous, and women do not participate in politics and labor. Rwanda seems an interesting case since they have women participating in politics and labor force but it is still a poor country relatively high maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate. Qatar, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia are among the wealthiest countries in the world but women do not participate in the labor force or politics. This biplot clearly states that if we want to measure well-being of populations of different countries, many measures are needed. Also, gender inequality is not automatically improving when gross national income per capita improves.

I select six variables for a new dataset and draw a graph. My new dataset consists of six variables describing how one does drink tea, what kind of tea, does one drink tea during lunch, does one drink tea with sugar, where one buys his or her tea, and the gender of the person.

# column names to keep in the dataset
keep_columns <- c("Tea", "How", "sugar", "where", "lunch", "sex")
# select the 'keep_columns' to create a new dataset
tea_time <- dplyr::select(tea, one_of(keep_columns))
# visualize the dataset
gather(tea_time) %>% ggplot(aes(value)) + geom_bar() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 8)) + facet_wrap("key", scales = "free")

## be dropped

Next Ill do multiple correspondence analysis (MCA) which is a method to analyze qualitative data and can be used to detect patterns or structure in the data as well as in dimension reduction.

# multiple correspondence analysis
mca <- MCA(tea_time, graph = FALSE)
# summary of the model
summary(mca)

Below is the graph of the results of MCA. The distance between variable categories gives a measure of their similarity.

s <- summary(mca)
# rounded percetanges of variance captured by each PC
s2 <- round(100*s$importance[2, ], digits = 1)
# create object pc_lab to be used as axis labels
s2_lab <- paste0(names(s2), "(", s2, "%)")
